AB  - This chapter presents several aspects regarding sensitive data privacy and cloud security for patients diagnosed with the chronic condition using homecare remote monitoring services. The wearable biosensors used by patients for remote monitoring (blood pressure, glucose level, pulse, ECG, or EEG) are based on the IoT platform hosted in the cloud. Sensitive data privacy can be achieved by anonymization in order to avoid the security risks, because remote monitoring are requested for the recordings of vital signs and sensitive personal information, such as name, address, telephone, date of birth, social insurance number, health status data, diagnosis results, and treatment schemas. The values of vital signs are useful in statistics for predictive modeling in order to understand and anticipate the behaviors of diseases. In addition, IoT security solutions to remote monitoring should involve setting the privacy levels for cloud types (private and public). The proposed approach is to split the privacy by levels of access that will ensure the security and privacy by using a different level of protection for different accounts (doctors and patients). © Springer Nature Switzerland AG 2020.
